<TITLE> German train drivers threaten new strikes over pay </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BERLIN, July 5 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - German train drivers threatened on Thursday to stage more warning strikes in coming weeks after rejecting a new wage offer from rail operator Deutsche Bahn. The head of the GDL drivers' union, which is seeking wage increases of up to 31 percent, left a meeting with Deutsche Bahn chief Hartmut Mehdorn in Frankfurt saying his union would hold more strikes to underline its demand for its own deal. Three days of strike action by GDL and two other unions caused massive disruptions for millions of passengers this week. Earlier, Deutsche Bahn raised its offer to 134,000 rail workers from all three unions to 3.4 percent plus a one-off payment of 450 euros, according to Margret Suckale, the group's head of personnel. The deal would run for 24 months. The Transnet and GDBA unions, which make up the bulk of rail workers, said the offer was inadequate but agreed to use it as a basis for further negotiations. "The amount and the length of time it runs for are not enough," said Alexander Kirchner, a leader of the negotiations for the two unions. Transnet and GDBA are demanding a seven percent pay rise. GDL head Manfred Schell took a tougher line and said his union would not join the other two groups if they reached a deal with Deutsche Bahn on the latest pay offer. Deutsche Bahn had previously offered two raises of two percent in 2008 and 2009, and a one-off payment of 300 euros ($407.5). Government-owned Deutsche Bahn has said 9,000 jobs would be put at risk if the company met the wage demands of the unio
